So not just Shiny, but across the ecosystem.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:40.720
So first, in terms of async, I'm mainly going to talk about async in the context of Shiny

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:41.720
itself.

00:03:42.119 --> 00:03:48.240
On the left here is the documentation for using promises in Shiny.

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:53.039
Some of you will have come across that, because it's been up for seven or eight years.

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:55.479
It's written by Joe Cheng himself.

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:01.399
What we've done earlier this year is update it to assume that when you're launching these

00:04:01.399 --> 00:04:06.839
async tasks, you're using Mirai to do so, which is right at the bottom.

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:09.720
And then on the right, what is Mirai?

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:12.360
Mirai is an RLib package.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:21.440
It's the package that I created to essentially bring modern async to R. And Mirai means future

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:23.519
in Japanese, by the way, in case you're wondering.

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:29.720
So it's a Japanese flavor of future, it's a Japanese future.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.440
So what do I mean by modern async?

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:39.000
Well, I like to use this analogy, email, because everyone should get this, everyone uses email,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.200
and basically before Mirai, what we had was what I call a scheduled fetch, but I mean

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:51.119
it doesn't really have a name, but it's when you have a desktop client and it just checks

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:55.040
for email every 15 minutes in the background, something like that.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:05:00.040
And we've all had this, you know, we've requested an OTP, we're waiting for the code, so we're

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:05.320
just constantly clicking refresh, it's like, you know, why haven't I got my code yet?

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:11.000
And that's sort of what we were doing before we had Mirai, and you can imagine when we

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.399
actually get an email, we get, the client says there is new email, then it actually

00:05:16.399 --> 00:05:18.959
goes to the server and fetches that back.

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:24.320
So if you have an email and it actually contains large attachments, you could actually be waiting

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:30.119
some time for that attachment to be downloaded before you can open up your email.

00:05:30.119 --> 00:05:35.720
So that's essentially the type of async, the experience you had before you had Mirai.

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:38.760
What Mirai brings you is basically push notification.

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:43.640
So again, this is the newer mobile experience.

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:49.239
We all know what happens, we get a notification on our phone, as soon as there's email on

00:05:49.239 --> 00:05:56.320
the server, notification pops up, and the difference here as well is when we get that

00:05:56.320 --> 00:05:59.320
notification, the email is already sitting on your phone.

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:04.959
So when you click into notification, the email will open up immediately.

00:06:04.959 --> 00:06:10.040
So this is just an analogy, but this actually corresponds very well to what's actually happening

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:16.040
under the hood when we talk about async in R and in Shiny.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:20.320
So this is pretty much what actually happens with Mirai versus not.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:24.880
So this is what I mean by modern async.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:32.399
So if you use Mirai within an extended task in Shiny, you get all of that, but you also

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:35.600
get all the other advantages of Mirai for free.

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:39.799
And I'm just going to spend a couple of minutes talking about some of the other advantages.

00:06:39.799 --> 00:06:45.399
If this goes over your head, just think, oh, wow, this sounds really advanced.

00:06:45.399 --> 00:06:52.920
But Mirai was designed thoughtfully, I'd like to say, I like to think, and on these four

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:57.679
pillars in that it has a modern foundation, which gives it the performance that it does,

00:06:57.679 --> 00:06:59.119
and it was designed for production.

00:06:59.119 --> 00:07:00.119
This is important.

00:07:00.119 --> 00:07:01.119
We'll get back to that.

00:07:01.119 --> 00:07:04.239
So you have the confidence to deploy it everywhere.

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:09.920
So in terms of modern foundation, it's built on NNG, which stands for Nano Message Next

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:10.920
Generation.

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:13.600
This is a high-performance messaging library.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:18.119
What this means is that we get the most optimal types of connections out of the box.

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:25.359
So this is inter-process communications, TCP, or even secure TLS, where we need that.

00:07:25.359 --> 00:07:33.359
We've also engineered BaseR's serialization mechanism to better support custom serialization

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:37.839
of newer cross-language data formats, such as Apache Array, such as if you're working

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:42.359
with Torch tensors.

00:07:42.359 --> 00:07:49.720
Because we have this foundation, Mirai can scale to millions of tasks over thousands

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:56.239
of connected processes, and it can do this all at 1,000 times the efficiency of anything

00:07:56.239 --> 00:07:59.600
that was available prior to Mirai.

00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:05.320
The zero latency promises are what I've just talked about, and this is probably the most

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:06.320
important point.

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:11.160
Mirai was designed for production, and because it was designed for production, it's designed

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.279
to be 100% reliable.

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:19.600
So it has this clear evaluation model, which matches, again, it matches what's actually

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:21.720
happening under the hood.

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:28.519
So that means the code that you write with Mirai, you can expect it to be executed consistently

00:08:28.519 --> 00:08:31.760
and transparently and reliably.

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:37.320
And we've minimized the complexity in the package itself, and we don't have any hidden

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:40.679
state.

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:45.719
And finally, you can really deploy this everywhere, so you can use Mirai to parallelize on your

00:08:45.719 --> 00:08:53.239
local machine, on remote machines where you have SSH, so this is any compute on your local

00:08:53.239 --> 00:08:56.919
network or any cloud instance that you spin up.

00:08:56.919 --> 00:09:01.919
And of course, if you have access to a high-performance compute cluster, you can use your scheduler

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:03.640
of choice.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:08.880
And Mirai has this concept of compute profiles, so these work in a modular way, so you can

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:14.679
be connected to all three types of resources at the same time, and you can do things like

00:09:14.679 --> 00:09:21.719
send different portions of compute to different destinations.

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:25.599
So that's all I'm going to be talking about on Mirai itself.

00:09:25.599 --> 00:09:28.919
Mirai is an RLIT package.

00:09:28.919 --> 00:09:32.960
It is now the primary async backend for Shiny.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:36.599
It is the built-in async evaluator in Plumber 2.

00:09:36.599 --> 00:09:43.080
It powers Parallel Per, and it's used in other parts of the Tidyverse as well, such

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:51.640
as in an upcoming release of Ragnar, and it's also used in Tidy models for things like hyperparameter

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:52.640
tuning.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:53.640
Great.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:10:01.000
So moving on to my second topic, this is open telemetry.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.559
This is something that's probably going to be new to most people in the audience.

00:10:07.559 --> 00:10:12.359
And open telemetry is all about observability at scale.

00:10:12.359 --> 00:10:16.719
This is especially important for something like a Shiny app, because a Shiny app can

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:17.719
be quite complicated.

00:10:17.719 --> 00:10:20.479
I mean, you can be doing a lot in a Shiny app.

00:10:20.479 --> 00:10:23.159
So you could be ingesting data from a database.

00:10:23.159 --> 00:10:30.979
You could be making a call to an API using HIDA2, and you can be doing computation using

00:10:30.979 --> 00:10:34.020
Mirai on another machine, for example.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:40.580
And to be able to see what's happening through all the layers of packages can be a challenge.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:45.500
And this is the problem that open telemetry is designed to solve.

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:48.719
So open telemetry has this concept of traces.

00:10:48.719 --> 00:10:52.280
A trace is just what happens in response and action.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:57.900
So in the context of a Shiny app, this could be someone clicking a button, which sets off

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:01.539
a reactive update.

00:11:01.539 --> 00:11:07.299
So when that happens, then everything that's the result of that action, you can see in

00:11:07.299 --> 00:11:13.760
spans, which is what happens in the various packages as a result of the action.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:17.260
And I won't spend too long explaining this, because I have a live demo where you can see

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:18.940
this in action.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:25.539
But first of all, why might you want to use data like this?

00:11:25.539 --> 00:11:33.059
Firstly, if you want to improve the performance of your Shiny app, you can easily see how

00:11:33.059 --> 00:11:38.179
long these spans are, and you can look at minimizing the span length.

00:11:38.179 --> 00:11:44.820
And also, if they're very heavily nested, you might look at reducing the amount of nesting

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:48.739
you have.

00:11:48.739 --> 00:11:56.460
Secondly, is you can see errors immediately.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:59.219
And these are errors that actually happen in actual use.

00:11:59.219 --> 00:12:03.619
So not just theoretical errors where you're just testing.

00:12:03.619 --> 00:12:06.739
If there's an error, they will show up in your spans.

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:10.219
Third point, all this data will be centralized.

00:12:10.219 --> 00:12:15.739
So even if you're doing things in other processes or even on other machines, you can receive

00:12:15.739 --> 00:12:21.500
this data in one place, in one dashboard that's easy for you to look at.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:25.340
And this final point is probably the best point.

00:12:25.340 --> 00:12:29.219
You can leave this on in production.

00:12:29.219 --> 00:12:34.299
So this isn't just when you're profiling your apps in development.

00:12:34.299 --> 00:12:37.619
For an actual deployed Shiny app, you can leave this on.

00:12:37.619 --> 00:12:41.260
And what this gives you is real-time monitoring.

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:48.059
So for example, if your Shiny app makes an API call and that API goes down, you'd be

00:12:48.059 --> 00:12:52.419
able to see that in real-time, and you can actually choose to get alerted to that.

00:12:52.419 --> 00:12:59.659
So if you wanted to mitigate that, that's possibly something that you can do.

00:12:59.659 --> 00:13:06.419
Right, so you might be wondering, how then do I enable this?

00:13:06.419 --> 00:13:08.140
How can I make use of this?

00:13:08.140 --> 00:13:11.580
Well, the good news is you don't need to do anything.

00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:14.140
You don't need to change any of your code.

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:16.099
We at Puzzit have done all the hard work.

00:13:16.099 --> 00:13:21.460
We've instrumented all the key packages where we think this will be useful to you.

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:28.140
So OpenTelemetry is already integrated in Mirai.

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:34.739
Versions of Shiny, HIDA2, and Elmer are going to be released imminently, not yet, but imminently,

00:13:34.739 --> 00:13:36.780
with this enabled.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:41.500
After that, we're going to be instrumenting Plumber2 and other packages where we think

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.140
this will be useful.

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:49.340
For you as a user or developer of a package or a Shiny app, all you need to do is install

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:55.619
the two packages, otel and otel-sdk, and then you set some environment variables.

00:13:55.619 --> 00:14:01.059
And these just tell the packages where to send the data.

00:14:01.059 --> 00:14:05.739
So these are the actual environment variables I'm using for the demo I'm just going to show

00:14:05.739 --> 00:14:08.880
you shortly.

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:14.820
This sends the data to an online service called LogFire.

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:18.179
But for you, you don't have to send any data over the internet.

00:14:18.179 --> 00:14:24.099
You can have a collector that's on your local network or even on the same machine.

00:14:24.099 --> 00:14:27.179
Great.

00:14:27.179 --> 00:14:28.539
So time for the demo.

00:14:28.539 --> 00:14:34.099
I'm going to do a demo that uses ShinyChat, Elmer, Mirai, and HIDA2, basically all of

00:14:34.099 --> 00:14:39.099
the packages that we've implemented for OpenTelemetry.

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:40.099
Great.

00:14:40.099 --> 00:14:47.299
So I'm going to exit out of here.

00:14:47.299 --> 00:14:51.179
This, by the way, is the interface for LogFire.

00:14:51.179 --> 00:14:55.099
You can see it's very empty at the moment.

00:14:55.099 --> 00:15:05.299
I am just going to, in our studio, just run this app.

00:15:05.299 --> 00:15:07.820
And this is just a chat app.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:13.179
We can see that, oh, some things have popped up already.

