00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:10.020
So if we look at these traces, we can see immediately there's red popping up.

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:16.459
And if we click through, we can actually see that this call actually failed.

00:18:16.459 --> 00:18:18.939
There's a 404 error.

00:18:18.939 --> 00:18:23.540
Basically the API only works for locations in the continental U.S., so we expect it to

00:18:23.540 --> 00:18:24.540
fail.

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:30.420
But you can easily see exactly the type of information that you can get.

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:36.979
So I'm gonna move back to the presentation.

00:18:36.979 --> 00:18:39.219
We've just been through these.

00:18:39.219 --> 00:18:43.459
They were just backups in case the live demo didn't work.

00:18:43.459 --> 00:18:49.060
So you can use this in a lot of ways, as I sort of briefly went through before.

00:18:49.060 --> 00:18:55.219
But one possible way you can use this is to improve the performance of your Shiny app.

00:18:55.219 --> 00:19:01.579
So this performance workflow was given by Joe Cheng back in 2019, and it was updated

00:19:01.579 --> 00:19:05.500
earlier this year by my colleague Barrett.

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:11.180
And essentially what we're seeing now with all the new tools that we have since 2019

00:19:11.180 --> 00:19:18.380
is, firstly, you can enable open telemetry, so you can see how long these spans are.

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:22.979
And for the long spans, you can then profile using ProfViz or another profiler to see where

00:19:22.979 --> 00:19:25.339
your code is slow.

00:19:25.339 --> 00:19:29.939
And to optimize slow code, I mean, this has always been true.

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:35.540
You can try and move as much work out of Shiny as possible.

00:19:35.540 --> 00:19:40.140
So pre-compute a lot of stuff before you even start a Shiny server, and this will quite

00:19:40.140 --> 00:19:42.400
often work.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:46.060
You can also try to make code faster.

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:47.859
And again, very often this actually works.

00:19:47.859 --> 00:19:52.260
And we have a lot more tools now versus in 2019.

00:19:52.260 --> 00:19:59.500
So instead of reading a CSV file, you can now use something like Duck Plier to read

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:00.540
a Parquet file.

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:03.900
So you can easily make your code faster.

00:20:03.900 --> 00:20:06.459
You can use caching, and this works sometimes.

00:20:06.459 --> 00:20:09.979
This is a feature that's built into Shiny itself.

00:20:09.979 --> 00:20:12.420
And you can use non-blocking reactivity.

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:15.859
So this is async with something like Mirai.

00:20:15.859 --> 00:20:21.780
And again, this will work sometimes, but this is going to work in many more cases now, because

00:20:21.780 --> 00:20:29.300
Mirai, if you remember, has 1,000 times the efficiency that you had access to before.

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:35.739
So you can use this in a lot more contexts.

00:20:35.739 --> 00:20:40.619
So there, I've nicely tied the second part of the talk back into the first part of my

00:20:40.619 --> 00:20:41.619
talk.

00:20:41.619 --> 00:20:45.819
So I think this is also a good place to leave this presentation.

00:20:45.819 --> 00:20:51.619
And I just want to say, it's been great to work with my colleagues on the Shiny team

00:20:51.619 --> 00:20:57.660
to roll these advances out, not just to Shiny, but across the ecosystem.

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:03.219
And I hope to either be here next year, or I'm sure another member of the Shiny team

00:21:03.219 --> 00:21:07.699
will be here, and they'll be talking about all the exciting new things that they've implemented

00:21:07.699 --> 00:21:08.699
over the year.

00:21:08.699 --> 00:21:09.699
So thank you very much.

00:21:09.699 --> 00:21:10.699
I'm happy to take questions.

00:21:10.699 --> 00:21:11.699
Thank you.

00:21:11.699 --> 00:21:12.699
Thank you.

00:21:12.699 --> 00:21:12.699


